                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Londo wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">This is incorrect. I have shown, and others have given accounts of actual events, where folks have attempted and completed Vxed and Tipt without any raid gear at all.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
You've shown that with a poorly balanced game element (charm) you can beat it.  I asked before: "how did these groups fare in KT/Ikkinz?".  Were you able to consistently win vxed/tipt without charm?  I would like to know.  I know on steelwarrior someone posted about a kind of project to prove this sort of thing but it didnt look like they went very far with it.  I know i haven't seen many casual players in KT at all yet.  Even a good number of the more casual raid guilds don't have any flagged members.  Its been over six months since i gained access.  I don't see any of the 'hardcore non-raiders' who play close to as much as i in KT even this long after i got into it.  That seems an awfully long gap to compensate for raiding.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Londo, I agree with you here actually. Totally. You are right that the Vxed and Tipt trials (not so much the sewers though) are really not doable without essentially using a poorly balanced game element such as charming mobs. I very much agree on that. There is no way in hell people without at least full suit of VT, EP, or Time gear or some mix there of can realistically do them without charming stuff. HOWEVER this is where I go back to my argument against raiding as the only means to acquire gear you need. I think it sucks to high heaven that GoD has come out and groups that want to pass the mountain trials either have to use a very poor game element like charm or they have to go through the 20 or so raids to get EP then the other 4 or 5 or so to get to Time and get geared up. That is SOOO messed up. And it is another reason EXACTLY why I argue against the current situation of raiding in EQ with no alternative means to gear up for new content. 
<br />

<br />
I don't even care about EP access anymore much less Time. I geared myself up through various means as I mentioned above but I dont really have any desire to do this content. It is getting old and I want to do more GoD content and the upcoming OOW. However I am not the majority of people. I have the luxury of having the gear (for the most part) to be a valuable member of the these groups. The vast majority of people not heavily raiding every night have no option without some serious farming and market trading for countless hours but to go back and do all those raids and join some humongous guild to get geared up just so they can do the new game expansion. I think that really sucks. Also, I have to say again what about the people that just cannot join those guilds? Say their schedule is all messed up. Or maybe they are just unlucky and can't get in, not because they are not good. As Shallow pointed out in his post there are only so many spots for billionaires and millionaires to go around. That is unfair in a "game". I used a real life analogy earlier to highlight that alternative paths are necessary but the fact is this a game and not real life. It should be "easier" to gain power and wealth etc... this is why we flock to games in the first place (not just EverQuest either); to do things we couldn't do in real life. 
<br />

<br />
People will argue but if everyone could have everything in a game then why would people try to do great stuff? Many of you had said this already. This problem doesn't exist in single player computer games and video games because of course you play alone so you have only your own selfishness to worry about. In the vast online world of games like EverQuest everyone is once again trying to beat their friends, just as in real life. I can understand the point from that aspect. I am not advocating that all people playing get everyone handed to them so there is no competition. Again in single player games designers dont worry about this because the computer engine could care less if you have "X super uber item_01" or not. It has no feelings. In games of this magnitude with many real human people playing though they have to worry about it. People want to "beat" each other. This is human nature. I am not suggesting that it go away either. I am suggesting that the game evolve to a point that allows people to gain power of equal quality through a different playstyle. This allows competition to exist for the person that will not or cannot join a guild for whatever his/her reasons are. As it currently stands there can be no real competition for the person that plays with small groups of friends. I am simply suggesting that the aspect of the game that absolutely *requires* big elitist guilds to exist is flawed in its ability to deliever maximum content, challenge, competition, and enjoyment to all players of different playstyles. 
<br />

<br />
Many that favor the existence of large raiding guilds will say "Oh casual players have lots of unexplored content". The trouble is, yes, sure there are some suck ass zones for those peopel that dont raid every single night. With suck ass gear in them. Again, the competition is gone for these people. They cannot compete. You want competition yet the game doesnt allow competition except in the avenue of one single play style. Such a huge, huge world and so many dynamic elements yet the only way to have competition on enormous magnitude for ALL players is for EVERYONE to raid 70 person encounters?? Gimme a break. There are quests as well. These are a good idea. The problem though is basically each and every long drawn out quest that a person could do to actually "compete" and gain nice gear requires some big huge enormous encounter at some point in the quest. It's just sad and bad game design. 
<br />

<br />

<br />
Sage Aaeron</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
