                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">What I think he's saying is that he's experienced the raiding to get to the top, and in order to do so, he sacrificed much of what he loved of the game play.  Thus the cost if you will, was far greater than the reward.  He's saying that the content should be achievable through more conservative means.  Not easier, not less time consuming, but a fashion that can be arranged for on a more flexible basis.  Which is what we've all been talking about all along... including the raiders.
<br />

<br />
Think about this catch-22:  Raiders are arguing to keep the same old progression in place, and yet they are crying about having to backflag/gear members they are desperate for.  It's _ok_ for a new member of a raiding guild to effecitvely be PL'd through the trials by folks now wearing gear FAR beyond what they had available when they first worked through it, but, it's NOT ok to come up with another method through the trials.
<br />

<br />
Let's put it on the table in a bald faced way folks:
<br />

<br />
Would it be acceptable if we had two paths through keyed zones that are not strictly raid level content.
<br />

<br />
A) Raid.  Very fast, realistically, this can be done in a days time (I mean 24 hours folks, not a 4 hour night of raiding).  This would include gathering the resources to spawn any triggered events/mobs and work your way through the fight
<br />

<br />
B) Casual.  Very slow, arduous, method involving many encounters that range from single group (potentially solo) to no more than 3 groups.  Difficulty would be high, higher than even the raid encounter.  Time involved would also be anything but trivial but, significant progress could be made in a night with 2 hours of time (by significant, I mean that one of the "many" encounters could be accomplished, at least potentially in 2 hours of work).  No fewer than 12 of these encounters would be required (note that the ENCOUNTER would be 2 hours, which does not include the time to gather items for triggered mobs, etc).
<br />

<br />
Note: both paths would be hard.  Both would have some time involved.  The raid path is significantly faster, offering, effectively, immediate gratification.  The "Casual" path is more flexible but, in reality, harder and certainly more time consuming.  Thus, the Casual path might actually take months to complete where the Raiders could do the same effort, by taking down the single raid mob, in a night.
<br />

<br />
Someone commented that group level content in a zone with Raid level mobs _should_ be locked out from non-raiding guilds.  Why?  The Raiders have the gear to trivialize content and now they have the primo grouping areas to trivialize leveling  (Raiding DOES= EXP, Iueamil, you missed that in your post, since raiders get access to the best leveling zones in the game).  I agree that any zone that is strictly raiding should be the personal play ground of raiders, but, I will never agree that group level content should be the pervue of raiders.
<br />

<br />
Finally: the Elementals offer more than just the raid level drops for gear, there is also the tradeskill drops.  Oddly, most raiders go through Aid Grimmel, and complain about how horrible it was doing tradeskills to get it while the tradeskillers LOVE doing tradeskills and only a few of them get access to Aid Grimmel... odd.  Why don't the tradeskillers get a zone of their own?  Their the ones who like doing the Tradeskills. Instead, the Raiders get still MORE stuff that they could care less about that effectively cuts others off who'd LOVE to have access to it.... and y'all wonder why this is surpassing 20 pages.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />GnarliAnna
<br />

<br />
Not flaming in a room of flammables is a nigh on impossible task!
<br />

<br />
